04313nam a22005415i 9780804776318DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047763187 a10.1515/97808047763182doi  a(DE-B1597)564669  a(OCoLC)1198931660  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE184.T53 H47 2009 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.8995410731 aHess, Julia Meredith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImmigrant Ambassadors :bCitizenship and Belonging in the Tibetan Diaspora /cJulia Meredith Hess. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Tibetan Transliteration -- tIntroduction: "We Will Always Hold Tibet in Our Hearts" -- t1. Tibet in Diaspora: Locating the Homeland from the Margins of Exile -- t2. India, New Mexico, and the Specter of Tibet: On the Trail of the Tibetan Diaspora -- t3. "Tibetanness" Where There Is No Tibet: Culture in a World of Nation-States -- t4. Refugees to Citizens, Tibetans, and the State -- t5. The Tibetan U.S. Resettlement Project: The Lottery, the "Lucky 1,000," and Immigrant Ambassadors -- t6. Tibetans in India: Deterritorialized Culture, Occidental Longing, and Global Imaginaries -- t7. A New Home in Diaspora: The First Years of the TUSRP, 1992-1996 -- t8. "Culture Is Your Base Camp": Tibetans in New Mexico, Youth, and Cultural Identity -- t9. Statelessness and the State: The Meanings of Citizenship -- tConclusion: Tibetans in the New World -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Tibetan diaspora began fifty years ago when the current Dalai Lama fled Lhasa and established a government-in-exile in India. For those fifty years, the vast majority of Tibetans have kept their stateless refugee status in India and Nepal as a reminder to themselves and the world that Tibet is under Chinese occupation and that they are committed to returning someday. In the 1990s, the U.S. Congress passed legislation that allowed 1,000 Tibetans and their families to immigrate to the United States; a decade later the total U.S. population includes some 10,000 Tibetans. Not only is the social fact of the migration-its historical and political contexts-of interest, but also how migration and resettlement in the U.S. reflect emergent identity formations among members of a stateless society. Immigrant Ambassadors examines Tibetan identity at a critical juncture in the diaspora's expansion, and argues that increased migration to the West is both facilitated and marked by changing understandings of what it means to be a twenty-first-century Tibetan-deterritorialized, activist, and cosmopolitan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCitizenshipxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPolitics and culture. 0aRefugees, TibetanxHistory. 0aTibetanszIndiaxEthnic identity. 0aTibetanszUnited StatesxEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804776318zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804776318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804776318.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles